urope -- t10. Place-Sensitive Citizenship: The Canadian Citizenship Regime until 1945 -- t11. The Diversification of Canadian Literature in English -- tSelected References -- tSelected Studies -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile multicultural composition of nations has become a catchword in public debates, few educators, not to speak of the general public, realize that cultural interaction was the rule throughout history. Starting with the Islam-Christian-Jewish Mediterranean world of the early modern period, this volume moves to the empires of the 18th and 19th centuries and the African Diaspora of the Black Atlantic. It ends with questioning assumptions about citizenship and underlying homogeneous "received" cultures through the analysis of the changes in various literatures. This volume clearly shows that the life-worlds of settled as well as migrant populations in the past were characterized by cultural change and exchange whether conflictual or peaceful. Societies reflected on such change in their literatures as well as in their concepts of citizenship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aCitizenship. 0aCultural pluralism. 0aEthnicity. 0aGlobalization. 0aGroup identity. 0aMulticulturalism. 0aRacism. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aAdanir, Fikret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarzig, Christiane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarzig, Christiane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHoerder, Dirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoerder, Dirk, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJenson, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct